So much soul that my body was regretting it the next day. Highlight: Watermelon Ice Tea that came with free refills. So refreshing and worth it! The crawfish beignets were surprisingly delicious! The fried chicken benedict was better than the catfish benedict because the catfish texture was too similar to the biscuit that it sat on so there was no distinction between meat and carb. The egg was perfectly poached on both. The hash was just bunch of mushy potatoes - needed a little crisp to it. The grits needed hot sauce - of course there is some on the table! Eat your food quickly! We realized that once it gets cold, the fat chemistry of the meal changes and becomes not as good. AKA - don't sit by the door during a cold day!

I thought the shrimps were kind of small, and there was an excessive amount of cheese on top of the dish. It was really greasy but the flavors they incorporated were delicious. My friend ordered the shrimp po boy sandwich which was mediocre at best. My other friend got Muffaletta Sandwich. It was so oily that the oil was dripping down her arm.

I've had the following: Crawfish Beignets Hushpuppies BBQ Pork Ribs Cornmeal Fried Shrimp Po'Boy Red Beans and Rice (with Andouille Sausage) For a group, their appetizer selection is great in that plates can be passed around the table quite easily and the portions, while small, did a good job at initiating conversation. Hushpuppies are exactly what they are, just deep fried puffs of savory starch. I am just not a fan of them. The BBQ pork ribs were mediocre in that I've had better ribs elsewhere and the meat was slightly dry, which is a huge no no. The Shrimp Po'boy went well with my date but he was not too enthused. My Red Beans and Rice dish was also mediocre in that the rice was not really anything out of this world and the sausage, which I prefer to be juicy, was not. My review is biased because Soul food is not my first to-go cuisine and other than the beignets, I give kudos to this place for initiating something new on this side of sketchy Polk Street. If you're a beignet lover, you have to check out Brenda's. They are melt in your mouth ooey-gooey goodness. They come out fresh, and warm, perfect for a chilly morning. Not going to lie, before Brenda's I've never even thought of a savory beignet. But I've got to say, I'm converted. Any beignet from Brenda's! Shrimp and grits is also a must if you're a shrimp lover like myself. It's quite filling so bring on your appetite. I had to take part of mine togo, but it still tasted just as good back home. One of the items I didn't quite care for though was the mimosa. I was pretty excited to have it alongside this delicious brunch, but it was a dud compared to everything else. But not drinking it made more room for the food.     5/11/2016

    I'm a slight fan but not a huge fan.

    Why?  Because I've hit numerous soul food establishments over the years that did not come attached with a high price tag but served equally amazing food.  

    That being said, I did enjoy eating here, with a friendly gathering and another time, on a date.  The interior reminds me of a warm kitchen but the sleek seating area and linen covered tables remove you once seated and the menu brings you back down to reality.

    I've had the following:

    Crawfish Beignets
    Hushpuppies
    BBQ Pork Ribs
    Cornmeal Fried Shrimp Po'Boy
    Red Beans and Rice (with Andouille Sausage)

    For a group, their appetizer selection is great in that plates can be passed around the table quite easily and the portions, while small, did a good job at initiating conversation.  We ordered several more of the appetizers to go around the table.  The crawfish beignets were a savory take on the classic sweet beignet and they were pretty tasty.  Hushpuppies are exactly what they are, just deep fried puffs of savory starch.  I am just not a fan of them.  The BBQ pork ribs were mediocre in that I've had better ribs elsewhere and the meat was slightly dry, which is a huge no no.  The Shrimp Po'boy went well with my date but he was not too enthused.  My Red Beans and Rice dish was also mediocre in that the rice was not really anything out of this world and the sausage, which I prefer to be juicy, was not.

    My review is biased because Soul food is not my first to-go cuisine and other than the beignets, I give kudos to this place for initiating something new on this side of sketchy Polk Street.  Personally, I was looking forward to smothered pork chops  ;-)

Got there at 10:30am and I wrote my name down on the chalkboard wait list. Took about an hour to get a seat for 2. Our order came out quickly which was a plus. We both got 2 guava mimosas along with the fried chicken egg Benedict with hash. Everything went so perfect together. It was all cooked perfect and just complimented everything so well. The food was great and was worth the wait. Whenever we are in town we would definitely stop by for brunch again.

    7/4/2017

    1 check-in

    If you're a beignet lover, you have to check out Brenda's. They are melt in your mouth ooey-gooey goodness. They come out fresh, and warm, perfect for a chilly morning. Not going to lie, before Brenda's I've never even thought of a savory beignet. But I've got to say, I'm converted. Any beignet from Brenda's! They had a Mardi Gras special with a little baby Jesus on top, so cute! Love that they have seasonal beignets! Super festive, and exciting for my taste buds! Shrimp and grits is also a must if you're a shrimp lover like myself. It's quite filling so bring on your appetite. I had to take part of mine togo, but it still tasted just as good back home. One of the items I didn't quite care for though was the mimosa. I was pretty excited to have it alongside this delicious brunch, but it was a dud compared to everything else. But not drinking it made more room for the food. And just like most Brunch places in the city, you should make time to come early, it can be a bit crowded, so make sure to bring a jacket to brave out the wind out front.
